<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: 29 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Joong Ang Daily
<http://joongangdaily.joins.com/200306/30/200306300042593239900090409041.html>

Family of 3 ill with botulism after eating tainted sausage
-------------------------
A Daegu family of three is in stable condition in the first known case in
Korea of food poisoning caused by the Clostridium botulinum bacterium.
A toxin produced by the bacterium can cause fatal paralysis of the
respiratory system. The bacterium is found in soil, from which it may be
carried to foods. It produces the toxin when improperly processed. Botulism
is not accompanied by diarrhea, as most other food poisonings are.
A couple and their 10-year-old daughter remained in the hospital yesterday
in Daegu after being admitted June 14, the National Institute of Health
said. The three had complained of difficulty breathing and general
weakness, it said.
The toxin was found in the stool of the 36-year-old woman, the institute
said. Her 40-year-old husband, and the daughter are also confirmed to have
been affected by the toxin. It was thought to come from sausages the 3 had
eaten.
A disease-control official, Kwon Jun-wook, said [the mother] and her
daughter were on respirators, but all 3 patients have improved markedly.
There have been no indications of additional patients, he added.
Clostridium botulinum bacteria become active in the absence of oxygen. Thus
canned food that has not been properly heat-processed provides optimum
conditions for their proliferation. But the bacteria also have been
associated with other foods improperly treated.
Signs of poisoning can appear up to 36 hours after consumption of tainted
food. Early symptoms also include blurred vision and excessive thirst. More
than 100 people are affected by the bacteria each year in the United
States, with a fatality rate of about 8 percent.
The institute advised thoroughly heating food before eating it. Since the
toxin is not associated with obvious signs, such as odor or taste, it
recommends disposing of food items when in doubt.
[by Ha Hyun-ock]
