[2]
Date: 29 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Korea Times
<http://times.hankooki.com/lpage/nation/200306/kt2003062917310511990.htm>

Botulism Patients Reported for First Time
Botulinus toxin poisoning has been reported for the first time in the
country, the National Institute of Health (NIH) said yesterday.
A 40-year-old Taegu man, his 36-year-old wife, and their 10-year-old
daughter have been hospitalized with botulism.
The 3 showed symptoms such as difficulty breathing and stiffness of their
limbs after eating sausages at a sauna nearby their home, the NIH said.
The NIH said botulinus toxin was only detected in [the mother], but it has
classified all 3 as botulism patients as they ate the same food and showed
similar symptoms.
Officials said they have collected sausages with the same serial number
from the manufacturer to determine whether they were responsible for the
food poisoning.
Normally caused by eating tainted canned food, the toxin paralyzes the
arms, legs and muscles of those infected. Eight percent of all cases end in
death, with about 100 cases recorded on average in the United States each year.
As it is one of the most potent toxins ever known, botulinus also poses a
major biological threat and is closely monitored in the United States and
other countries.
A NIH official said the cases seem unrelated to biological terrorist acts
but they have stepped up surveillance just in case.
He said people should seek immediate hospital treatment if they suffer from
breathing difficulties after eating canned food.
[By Soh Ji-young]
